While profiling a small program that runs commands that accepts the result into a {{bson.Raw}}, I noticed that the command path appears to {{bson.Unmarshal}} once into my {{bson.Raw}} argument, however then a second time into a locally declared {{bson.M}} for a {{debugf}} message.

https://github.com/go-mgo/mgo/blob/b6e2fa371e64216a45e61072a96d4e3859f169da/session.go#L3205-L3206

Snippet
{code}
	if result != nil {
		err = bson.Unmarshal(data, result)
		if err == nil {
			var res bson.M 
			bson.Unmarshal(data, &res) // <= Additional Unmarshal
			debugf("Run command unmarshaled: %#v, result: %#v", op, res)
		} else {
			debugf("Run command unmarshaling failed: %#v", op, err)
			return err
		}
	}
{code}

I'm assuming the double decoding is on accident as I also notice that other paths, such as through {{One(result)}} and {{Next(result)}}, their {{debugf()}} messages log the result structure provided by the user.

Running {{bson.UnmarshalJSON}} on a string such as 
{code}
{"foo" : 123}
{code}
causes a panic. This is due to the space between the key {{"foo"}} and the colon symbol. The source of the bug can be traced to here: https://github.com/10gen/mgo/blob/v2/internal/json/decode.go#L1044

The {{unquote}} function is passed the byte array {{name}}, which does not have whitespace trimmed.
